<chapter xml:id="chapter-equiv-rel" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Equivalence relations</title>

<section xml:id="section-equiv-rel-motivation">
<title>Motivation</title>

<p> There are often situations where we want to group certain elements of a set together as being <q>the same.</q> </p>

<example><p>
	At the end of this course, your instructor will assign each student a grade.
	In this system, every student who receives a <q>B</q> had roughly the same performance in the course
	(in principle, anyways).
	That is, consider the set of all students in this course <mdash />
	from the point of view of the grading system,
	the students in the subset of <q>B</q> students are all <term>equivalent</term> in performance.
</p></example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-equiv-rel-basics-and-examples">
<title>Basics and examples</title>

<p>
What properties should a relation on a set have to be useful as a notion of <q>equivalence</q>?
<ul>
	<li>
		Each object in the set should be equivalent to itself.
		So the relation should be <term><xref ref="definition-relations-reflexive" text="title" /></term>.
	</li>
	<li>
		Equivalence should be bidirectional.
		That is, a pair of equivalent objects should be equivalent to <em>each other</em>.
		So the relation should be <term><xref ref="definition-relations-symmetric" text="title" /></term>.
	</li>
	<li>
		We should be able to infer equivalence from chains of equivalence.
		So the relation should be <term><xref ref="definition-relations-transitive" text="title" /></term>.
	</li>
</ul>
<dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>equivalence relation</title>
		<idx><h>equivalence</h><h>relation</h></idx>
		<idx><h>relation(s)</h><h>equivalence</h></idx>
		<p>
		a relation on a set that is
		<term><xref ref="definition-relations-reflexive" text="title" /></term>,
		<term><xref ref="definition-relations-symmetric" text="title" /></term>, and
		<term><xref ref="definition-relations-transitive" text="title" /></term>
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\mathord{\equiv}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>a \equiv b</m></usage>
			<description>
				<m>a</m> is related to <m>b</m> by the equivalence relation <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m>;
				in other words, <m>a</m> is somehow equivalent to <m>b</m>
			</description>
		</notation>
		<p>
		symbol for an abstract equivalence relation
		(instead of the letter <m>R</m> that we've been using for abstract relations up until now)
		</p>
	</li>
</dl>
</p>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement><p>
		Let <m>\mathscr{L}</m> be the set of all possible logical statements built out of the statement variables <m>p_1, p_2, p_3, \dotsc</m>.
		Show that
		<xref ref="definition-logic-equiv-equiv-statements" text="custom">logical equivalence of statements</xref>
		is an equivalence relation on <m>\mathscr{L}</m>.
	</p></statement>
	<solution>
		<case><title>Reflexive</title><p>
			We have <m>A \lgcequiv A</m> for every statement <m>A</m>,
			since <m>A</m> has the same truth table as itself.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Symmetric</title><p>
			If <m>A \lgcequiv B</m>, then <m>A,B</m> have the same truth table,
			so <m>B \lgcequiv A</m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Transitive</title><p>
			If <m>A \lgcequiv B</m> and <m>B \lgcequiv C</m>,
			then <m>A</m> has the same truth table as <m>B</m>,
			which has the same truth table as <m>C</m>.
			So <m>A</m> has the same truth table as <m>C</m>, <ie /> <m>A \lgcequiv C</m>.
		</p></case>
	</solution>
</problem>

<p>
Here is an important equivalence relation on <m>\N</m> or on <m>\Z</m>.
<dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>equivalence modulo <m>n</m></title>
		<idx>modulo</idx>
		<idx><h>equivalence</h><h>modulo</h></idx>
		<p>
		an equivalence of integers,
		where two integers are equivalent if they have the same remainder when divided by <m>n</m>
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>m_1 \equiv_n m_2</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>m_1 \equiv_n m_2</m></usage>
			<description>integers <m>m_1,m_2</m> are equivalent modulo <m>n</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> integers <m>m_1,m_2</m> are equivalent modulo <m>n</m> </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<exercise><p> Verify that equivalence modulo <m>n</m> is an equivalence relation. </p></exercise>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-equiv-rel-classes">
<title>Classes, partitions, and quotients</title>

<p>
As desired (see <xref ref="section-equiv-rel-motivation" />),
an equivalence relation can be used to group equivalent objects together.
</p>

<example><p>
	Consider <m>\mathord{\equiv_5}</m> on <m>\N</m>.
	Notice that the elements in each of the following sets are all equivalent to each other with respect to <m>\mathord{\equiv_5}</m>.
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> \{ 0, 5, 10, 15, \dotsc \} </mrow>
		<mrow> \{ 1, 6, 11, 16, \dotsc \} </mrow>
		<mrow> \{ 2, 7, 12, 17, \dotsc \} </mrow>
		<mrow> \{ 3, 8, 13, 18, \dotsc \} </mrow>
		<mrow> \{ 4, 9, 14, 19, \dotsc \} </mrow>
	</md>
	Also notice that <m>\N</m> is the
	<term><xref ref="definition-sets-disjoint-sets" text="custom">disjoint</xref> <xref ref="definition-sets-disjoint-union" text="custom">union</xref></term>
	of the above sets.
	</p><p>
	In fact, we could do the same for every divisor <m>n</m>, not just for <m>n = 5</m>,
	as <m>\N</m> is also the disjoint union of the sets
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> \{ \, 0, \, n, \, 2n, \, 3n, \, \dotsc \, \}, </mrow>
		<mrow> \{ \, 1, \, n+1, \, 2n+1, \, 3n+1, \, \dotsc \, \}, </mrow>
		<mrow> \{ \, 2, \, n+2,\, 2n+2,\, 3n+2, \, \dotsc \, \}, </mrow>
		<mrow> \vdots </mrow>
		<mrow> \{ \, n-1, \, n + (n-1), \, 2n + (n-1), \, 3n + (n-1), \, \dotsc \, \}, </mrow>
	</md>
	and again elements in each of the above sets are all equivalent to each other with respect to <m>\mathord{\equiv_n}</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>equivalence class (of an element <m>a</m>)</title>
		<idx><h>equivalence</h><h>class</h></idx>
		<idx>class (for an equivalence relation)</idx>
		<p>
			the subset of <m>A</m> consisting of all elements that are equivalent to the given element <m>a \in A</m>,
			relative to a specific equivalence relation <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m> on <m>A</m>;
			<ie /> the set <me> \setdef{x\in A}{ x \equiv a } </me>
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\eqclass{a}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\eqclass{a}</m></usage>
			<description>the equivalence class of the element <m>a \in A</m> relative to some specific equivalence relation on <m>A</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> the equivalence class of the element <m>a \in A</m> relative to some specific equivalence relation on <m>A</m> </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example xml:id="example-equiv-rel-classes-mod-5">
	<title>Equivalence classes of natural numbers modulo <m>5</m></title>
	<p>
	If we divide <m>8</m> by <m>5</m>, we get <m>1</m> with <m>3</m> remainder.
	So the equivalence class of <m>8</m> relative to <m>\mathord{\equiv_5}</m> consists of all natural numbers that have remainder <m>3</m> when divided by <m>5</m>:
	<me> \eqclass{8} = \{ 3, 8, 13, 18, \dotsc \} </me>.
	Now, <m>3</m> is in this class because when we divide <m>3</m> by <m>5</m> we get <m>0</m> with <m>3</m> remainder.
	But if we had started with <m>3</m> instead of <m>8</m>,
	we would have also said that the equivalence class of <m>3</m> relative to <m>\mathord{\equiv_5}</m> consists of all natural numbers that have remainder <m>3</m> when divided by <m>5</m>:
	<me> \eqclass{3} = \{ 3, 8, 13, 18, \dotsc \} </me>.
	</p>
</example>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-equiv-rel-properties">
<!-- \label{PROPOSITION::equiv.relation.properties} -->
	<title>Properties of equivalence classes</title>
	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m> is an equivalence relation on a nonempty set <m>A</m>.
		<ol>
			<li xml:id="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-element-in-own-class">
			<!-- \label{PROPOSITION::element.in.own.class} -->
				For every <m>a \in A</m>, we have <m>a \in \eqclass{a}</m>.
			</li>
			<li xml:id="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-same-class-equivalent">
				For <m>a,a_1,a_2 \in A</m> with <m>a_1,a_2 \in \eqclass{a}</m>,
				we have <m>a_1 \equiv a_2</m>.
			</li>
			<li xml:id="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-equal-classes">
			<!-- \label{PROPOSITION::equal.classes} -->
				For each pair <m>a_1,a_2 \in A</m>,
				we have <m>a_1 \equiv a_2</m> if and only if <m>\eqclass{a_1} = \eqclass{a_2}</m>.
			</li>
			<li xml:id="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-disjoint-classes">
				For each pair <m>a_1,a_2 \in A</m>,
				we have <m>a_1 \not\equiv a_2</m> if and only if <m>\eqclass{a_1} \intersection \eqclass{a_2} = \emptyset</m>.
			</li>
		</ol>
	</p></statement>
	<proof>
		<title>Proof of <xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-element-in-own-class" text="local">Statement</xref></title>
		<p> This is just the reflexive property, <m>a \equiv a</m>. </p>
	</proof>
	<proof>
		<title>Proof of <xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-same-class-equivalent" text="local">Statement</xref></title>
		<p>
		If <m>a_1,a_2 \in \eqclass{a}</m>,
		then by definition we have both <m>a_1 \equiv a</m> and <m>a_2 \equiv a</m>.
		Applying symmetry to the latter equivalence, we may write
		<m>a_1 \equiv a \equiv a_2</m>, to which we may apply transitivity to obtain
		<m>a_1 \equiv a_2</m>, as desired.
		</p>
	</proof>
	<proof>
		<title>Proof of <xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-equal-classes" text="local">Statement</xref></title>
		<case direction="forward"><p>
			Suppose <m>a_1 \equiv a_2</m>.
			To verify <m>\eqclass{a_1} = \eqclass{a_2}</m>,
			we follow the <xref ref="test-sets-equality" text="custom">Test for Set Equality</xref>.
			First, assume <m>x</m> is an arbitrary element in <m>\eqclass{a_1}</m>.
			Then <m>x \equiv a_1 \equiv a_2</m>, so <m>x \equiv a_2</m> by the transitive property.
			Therefore, <m>x \in \eqclass{a_2}</m>, as required.
			This shows that <m>\eqclass{a_1} \subseteq \eqclass{a_2}</m>;
			the argument to show <m>\eqclass{a_2} \subseteq \eqclass{a_1}</m> is almost exactly the same,
			just using the symmetric property to first obtain <m>a_2 \equiv a_1</m>.
		</p></case>
		<case direction="backward"><p>
			By <xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-element-in-own-class" text="local">Statement</xref> of this proposition,
			we have <m>a_1 \in \eqclass{a_1}</m>.
			If we assume <m>\eqclass{a_1} = \eqclass{a_2}</m>,
			then we also have <m>a_1 \in \eqclass{a_2}</m>, which means that <m>a_1 \equiv a_2</m>,
			as required.
		</p></case>
	</proof>
	<proof>
		<title>Proof of <xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-disjoint-classes" text="local">Statement</xref></title>
		<p>
		Let us prove the equivalent <q>double contrapositive</q> biconditional <m>a_1 \equiv a_2 \lgcequiv \eqclass{a_1} \intersection \eqclass{a_2} \ne \emptyset</m>.
		(See <xref ref="wexample-logic-equiv-negate-biconditional" />.)
		</p>
		<case direction="forward"><p>
			Suppose <m>a_1 \equiv a_2</m>.
			Then <m>\eqclass{a_1} = \eqclass{a_2}</m> by <xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-equal-classes" text="local">Statement</xref>,
			so <me> \eqclass{a_1} \intersection \eqclass{a_2} = \eqclass{a_1} \intersection \eqclass{a_1} = \eqclass{a_1} </me>.
			But <m>\eqclass{a_1}</m> is nonempty by <xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-element-in-own-class" text="local">Statement</xref>.
		</p></case>
		<case direction="backward"><p>
			Suppose <m>\eqclass{a_1} \intersection \eqclass{a_2} \ne \emptyset</m>.
			Then there exists some element <m>x \in A</m> that is in both <m>\eqclass{a_1}</m> and <m>\eqclass{a_2}</m>,
			so that both <m>x \equiv a_1</m> and <m>x \equiv a_2</m>.
			By the symmetric property, we have <m>a_1 \equiv x</m>, and combining this with <m>x \equiv a_2</m> in the transitive property gives <m>a_1 \equiv a_2</m>.
		</p></case>
	</proof>
</proposition>

<p>
<xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-equal-classes" text="type-local">Statement</xref>
of <xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties" />
tells us that any member of an equivalence class may be used to define the class.
<dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>equivalence class representative</title>
		<idx><h>equivalence</h><h>class</h><h>representative</h></idx>
		<idx><h>class (for an equivalence relation)</h><h>representative</h></idx>
		<p>
		an element <m>a \in A</m> used to define the equivalence class
		<me> \eqclass{a} = \setdef{x\in A}{ x \equiv a } </me>
		</p>
	</li>
	<li xml:id="definition-equiv-rel-complete-rep-set">
		<title>complete set of equivalence class representatives</title>
		<idx><h>equivalence</h><h>class</h><h>set of representatives</h></idx>
		<idx><h>class (for an equivalence relation)</h><h>representative</h><h>complete set</h></idx>
		<p>
		a subset <m>C \subseteq A</m> so that for each <m>x \in A</m>
		there exists <em>exactly one</em> <m>a \in C</m> so that <m>x \in \eqclass{a}</m>
		</p>
	</li>
</dl>
Remember that elements that are equivalent to one another relative to some equivalence relation are viewed to be <q>essentially the same</q> from the point of view of the property used to define the equivalence relation.
So <em>different but equivalent elements</em> become interchangeable
(see <xref ref="section-equiv-rel-motivation" />).
When we have a complete set of representatives for the equivalence classes,
we are deciding to always interchange an element for the chosen representative of the class containing that element.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-equiv-rel-class-reps-mod-5">
	<title>A complete set of equivalence class representatives for natural numbers modulo <m>5</m></title>
	<p>
	Continuing <xref ref="example-equiv-rel-classes-mod-5" />,
	we <em>could</em> represent the class of numbers that have remainder <m>3</m> by the number <m>8</m>:
	<me> \eqclass{8} = \{ 3, 8, 13, 18, \dotsc \} </me>.
	But it seems more <q>natural</q> to represent this class by the number <m>3</m>:
	<me> \eqclass{3} = \{ 3, 8, 13, 18, \dotsc \} </me>.
	</p><p>
	Notice that each of the numbers <m>0,1,2,3,4</m> has a different remainder when divided by <m>5</m>,
	so no two of them are equivalent.
	That also means that each is in a different class
	(<xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-disjoint-classes" text="type-local">Statement</xref>
	of <xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties" />).
	But when we go past <m>4</m>, the remainders when divided by <m>5</m> start repeating:
	each of the numbers in the list <m>5,6,7,8,9</m> has the same remainder as the number in the corresponding position in the list <m>0,1,2,3,4</m>.
	And then the remainders repeat again when we go past <m>9</m>.
	And so on.
	So it seems <q>natural</q> to use <m>0,1,2,3,4</m> as a complete set of representatives of the equivalence classes for <m>\N</m> modulo <m>5</m>:
	<md>
		<mrow> \eqclass{0} \amp = \{ 0, 5, 10, 15, \dotsc \}, </mrow>
		<mrow> \eqclass{1} \amp = \{ 1, 6, 11, 16, \dotsc \}, </mrow>
		<mrow> \eqclass{2} \amp = \{ 2, 7, 12, 17, \dotsc \}, </mrow>
		<mrow> \eqclass{3} \amp = \{ 3, 8, 13, 18, \dotsc \}, </mrow>
		<mrow> \eqclass{4} \amp = \{ 4, 9, 14, 19, \dotsc \}. </mrow>
	</md>
	</p>
</example>

<p>
The definition of <term><xref ref="definition-equiv-rel-complete-rep-set" text="title" /></term>
implicitly assumes that the equivalence classes <q>fill up</q> the whole set <m>A</m>.
But that is always precisely the case.
<dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>partition</title>
		<idx>partition</idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partition</h></idx>
		<p> a collection of subsets of a set <m>A</m> that are pairwise disjoint and whose union is <m>A</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>partition cell</title>
		<idx><h>partition</h><h>cell</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partition</h><h>cell</h></idx>
		<p> one of the subsets that make up a partition of a set </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<figure xml:id="figure-equiv-rel-partition">
	<caption>
		A diagram illustrating a <term>partition</term> of a set,
		so that <m>A = A_1 \sqcup A_2 \sqcup A_3 \sqcup \dotsb \sqcup A_n</m>.
	</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-equiv-rel-partition" width="56.1%">
		<description>A diagram illustrating a partition of a set.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="equiv-rel.d/partition.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<remark><p>
	In essence, <term>partition</term> is just a synonym for <term>disjoint union</term>.
	So a collection of subsets form a partition when each element of the set is in <em>exactly</em> one partition cell.
</p></remark>

<note><p>
	It is not necessary for a partition of a set to be made up of a <em>finite</em>
	(or even <em>countable</em>) number of cells; see the examples below.
</p></note>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-equiv-rel-classes-form-partition">
	<title>Equivalence classes form a partition</title>
	<statement><p>
		If <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m> is an equivalence relation on a set <m>A</m>,
		then the equivalence classes with respect to <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m> are a partition of <m>A</m>.
	</p></statement>
	<proof><title>Proof idea</title><p>
		This theorem claims that every element of <m>A</m> is in <em>exactly one</em> equivalence class.
		But this follows from the statements of <xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties" />.
	</p></proof>
</theorem>

<example>
	<title>Equivalence classes modulo <m>n</m></title>
	<p>
	Generalizing <xref ref="example-equiv-rel-class-reps-mod-5" />,
	each of the numbers <m>0,1,2,3,\dots,n-1</m> is its own remainder when divided by <m>n</m>.
	And then the pattern of remainders repeats, starting over at remainder <m>0</m>,
	when we continue on to the numbers <m>n,n+1,\dotsc</m>.
	So <m>0,1,2,3,\dots,n-1</m> is a complete set of equivalence class representatives,
	and the classes modulo <m>n</m> partition <m>\N</m> into the disjoint subsets
	<md>
		<mrow> \eqclass{0} \amp = \{ \, 0, \, n, 2n, \, 3n, \, \dotsc \, \}, </mrow>
		<mrow> \eqclass{1} \amp = \{ \, 1, \, n+1, 2n+1, \, 3n+1, \, \dotsc \, \}, </mrow>
		<mrow> \eqclass{2} \amp = \{ \, 2, \, n+2, 2n+2, \, 3n+2, \, \dotsc \, \}, </mrow>
		<mrow> \phantom{\eqclass{0}} \amp \vdots </mrow>
		<mrow> \eqclass{n-1} \amp = \{ \, n-1, \, 2n-1, 3n-1, \, 4n-1, \, \dotsc \, \}. </mrow>
	</md>
	</p>
</example>

<example><p>
	Let <m>\mathscr{L}</m> be the set of all lines in the plane,
	and consider <m>\ell_1 \equiv \ell_2</m> if <m>\ell_1, \ell_2</m> are parallel.
	Then <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m> partitions <m>\mathscr{L}</m> into sets of parallel lines.
</p></example>

<example>
	<p>
	Recall that for alphabet <m>\Sigma</m>,
	<m>\words{\Sigma}_n</m> is the subset of <m>\words{\Sigma}</m> consisting of all words whose length is exactly <m>n</m>.
	Then <me>\words{\Sigma}_0, \words{\Sigma}_1, \words{\Sigma}_2, \dotsc</me>
	is a partition of <m>\words{\Sigma}</m>.
	(See <xref ref="exercise-sets-words-disjoint-union-of-lengths" />.)
	</p><p>
	Recall that a relation on <m>\words{\Sigma}</m> can be defined as a subset of <m>\words{\Sigma} \cartprod \words{\Sigma}</m>.
	So consider the relation <m>R</m> on <m>\words{\Sigma}</m> defined by
	<me>
		R \;\; =\;\;
		(\words{\Sigma}_0 \cartprod \words{\Sigma}_0)
		\;\; \sqcup \;\; (\words{\Sigma}_1 \cartprod \words{\Sigma}_1)
		\;\; \sqcup \;\; (\words{\Sigma}_2 \cartprod \words{\Sigma}_2)
		\;\; \sqcup \;\; \dotsb
	</me>
	Then <m>R</m> is the equivalence relation on <m>\words{\Sigma}</m> where <m>w \mathrel{R} y</m> if <m>\length{w} = \length{y}</m>,
	and its equivalence classes are precisely the sets <m>\words{\Sigma}_n</m>, <m>n\ge 0</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-equiv-rel-from-partition">
	<title>Partitions arise from equivalence relations</title>
	<statement><p>
		Given a partition of a set <m>A</m>,
		there exists an equivalence relation <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m> on <m>A</m> whose equivalence classes are precisely the cells of the partition.
	</p></statement>
	<proof><title>Proof idea</title><p>
		Given a partition of <m>A</m>,
		for each <m>a \in A</m> there exists exactly one partition cell containing <m>a</m>.
		So define <m>a_1 \equiv a_2</m> to mean <q>elements <m>a_1,a_2</m> are contained in the same partition cell of <m>A</m>.</q>
	</p></proof>
</theorem>

<remark><p>
	<xref ref="theorem-equiv-rel-classes-form-partition" /> and <xref ref="theorem-equiv-rel-from-partition" />
	combine to provide, for each set <m>A</m>, a bijective correspondence
	<me> \{ \text{equivalence relations on } A \} \;\; \longleftrightarrow \;\; \{ \text{partitions of } A \}. </me>
</p></remark>

<problem xml:id="wexample-equiv-rel-equivrel-from-partition">
	<title>Determining an equivalence relation from a partition</title>
	<statement><p>
		Determine an explicit equivalence relation <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m> on <m>\Z</m> for which the equivalence classes give the following partition.
		<me>
			\Z \;\; = \;\; \dotsb
			\;\; \sqcup \;\; \{ -3, -2, -1 \}
			\;\; \sqcup \;\; \{ 0, 1, 2 \}
			\;\; \sqcup \;\; \{ 3, 4, 5 \}
			\;\; \sqcup \;\; \dotsb
		</me>
	</p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Notice that each cell in the partition contains a multiple of <m>3</m> along with the next two consecutive integers.
		So one way to explicitly define the corresponding equivalence relation is:
		for <m>a,b \in \Z</m>, define <m>a \equiv b</m> to be true if there exists <m>n \in \Z</m> such that <m>3 n \le a,b \le 3 n + 2</m>.
		(<em>Note:</em> Details showing that this is an equivalence relation are omitted.)
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>quotient (of a set <m>A</m> relative to an equivalence relation <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m>)</title>
		<idx>quotient</idx>
		<idx><h>equivalence</h><h>relation</h><h>quotient</h></idx>
		<idx><h>relation(s)</h><h>equivalence</h><h>quotient</h></idx>
		<p> the subset of <m>\powset{A}</m> whose elements are the equivalence classes of <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m> A / \mathord{\equiv} </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> A / \mathord{\equiv} </m></usage>
			<description>the quotient of <m>A</m> relative to equivalence relation <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p>
		the quotient of <m>A</m> relative to equivalence relation <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m>,
		so that <me> (A / \mathord{\equiv}) = \setdef{\eqclass{a}}{a \in A} </me>
		</p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example>
	<title>A quotient described by class representatives</title>
	<p>
	Consider the partition of <m>\Z</m> from <xref ref="wexample-equiv-rel-equivrel-from-partition" />,
	and the corresponding equivalence relation <m>\mathrel{\equiv}</m>.
	To describe <m>\Z / \equiv</m>, we just need to pick a representative of each class.
	The most obvious way in this case is <me> (\Z / \mathord{\equiv}) = \{ \dotsc, \eqclass{-3}, \eqclass{0}, \eqclass{3}, \eqclass{6}, \dotsc \} </me>.
	</p>
</example>

<problem>
	<title>Determining a quotient</title>
	<statement><p>
		Let <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m> represent the equivalence relation on <m>\Z</m> defined by
		<ol marker="(i)">
			<li> <m>0 \equiv 0</m>, and </li>
			<li>
				for non-zero <m>m,n \in \Z</m>,
				<md><mrow> m \amp \equiv n \amp \amp \text{if} \amp \frac{m}{\abs{m}} \amp = \frac{n}{\abs{n}} </mrow></md>.
			</li>
		</ol>
		Determine the corresponding partition and quotient of <m>\Z</m>.
	</p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		First notice that <m>0</m> will be in an equivalence class all by itself.
		Next, consider the values that <m>m/\abs{m}</m> can possibly take.
		<ul>
			<li> If <m>m \gt 0</m>, then <m>\abs{m} = m</m> so <m>m/\abs{m} = 1</m>. </li>
			<li> If <m>m \lt 0</m>, then <m>\abs{m} = - m</m> so <m>m/\abs{m} = -1</m>. </li>
		</ul>
		So this equivalence relation is just a fancy way of saying that <m>m,n</m> have the <em>same sign</em>.
		Therefore, all positive numbers will be in the same equivalence class,
		and all negative numbers will be in the same equivalence class.
		It now makes sense that <m>0</m> is in a class by itself, since <m>0</m> is neither positive nor negative.
		The partition of <m>\Z</m> corresponding to <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m> is then
		<me>
			\Z \;\; = \;\; \{ \dotsc, -3, -2, -1 \}
			\;\; \sqcup \;\; \{ 0 \}
			\;\; \sqcup \;\; \{ 1, 2, 3, \dotsc \}
		</me>.
		To describe <m>\Z / \mathord{\equiv}</m>, we just need to pick a representative of each equivalence class.
		One possibility is
		<me> \Z = \eqclass{-1} \sqcup \eqclass{0} \sqcup \eqclass{1} </me>,
		so that
		<me> (\Z / \mathord{\equiv}) = \{ \eqclass{-1}, \eqclass{0}, \eqclass{1} \} </me>.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<p><dl width="narrow"><li>
	<title>natural projection (on a set <m>A</m> relative to an equivalence relation <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m>)</title>
	<idx><h>natural</h><h>projection</h></idx>
	<idx><h>projection</h><h>natural (onto a quotient)</h></idx>
	<p> the function <m>A \to (A / \mathord{\equiv})</m> defined by <m>a \mapsto \eqclass{a}</m> </p>
</li></dl></p>

<note><p> The natural projection <m>A \to (A / \mathord{\equiv})</m> is always surjective, but it is almost never injective. </p></note>

<example>
	<title>Natural projection modulo-<m>5</m></title>
	<p>
	Recall that <m>\mathord{\equiv}_5</m> represents the modulo-<m>5</m> equivalence relation on <m>\N</m>.
	In <xref ref="example-equiv-rel-class-reps-mod-5" /> we determined that there are five equivalence classes,
	represented by elements <m>0,1,2,3,4</m>,
	so that <me> (\N / \mathord{\equiv}_5) = \{\eqclass{0},\eqclass{1},\eqclass{2},\eqclass{3},\eqclass{4}\} </me>.
	Below are some examples of images of elements under the natural projection.
	<md><mrow>
		2 \amp \mapsto \eqclass{2} \amp
		7 \amp \mapsto \eqclass{2} \amp
		104 \amp \mapsto \eqclass{4} \amp
		76 \amp \mapsto \eqclass{1} \amp
		2045 \amp \mapsto \eqclass{0}
	</mrow></md>.
</p></example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-equiv-rel-important-exmps">
<title>Important examples</title>

<example>
	<title>Equality is the strongest form of equivalence</title>
	<p>
	The <q>strongest</q> equivalence relation on a set <m>A</m> is the identity relation,
	where <m>a \equiv b</m> if and only if <m>a = b</m>.
	In this case, each equivalence class is a singleton:
	<m>[a] = \{a\}</m> for each <m>a \in A</m>.
	This equivalence relation yields the <q>finest</q> or most <q>granular</q> partition of <m>A</m>,
	into the union of all the singleton sets in <m>\powset{A}</m>.
	Here, the quotient <m>A/\equiv</m> is essentially the same as <m>A</m>:
	the natural projection <m>A \to (A/\equiv)</m> is a bijection.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-equiv-rel-even-and-odd-mod-2">
	<title>Even and odd</title>
	<p>
	We can partition <m>\N</m> into the subsets of even and odd numbers.
	This is the same partition obtained from the modulo-<m>2</m> equivalance relation <m>\mathord{\equiv}_2</m>,
	and we have quotient <me> (\N / \mathord{\equiv}_2) = \{ \eqclass{0}, \eqclass{1} \} </me>.
	This quotient is how we construct <em>boolean algebra</em> (see <xref ref="chapter-bool-alg" />).
	The convention <m> 1 + 1 = 0 </m> in boolean algebra comes from defining addition in the quotient so that
	<me> \eqclass{1} + \eqclass{1} = \eqclass{1 + 1} = \eqclass{2} = \eqclass{0} </me>.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Modulo-<m>n</m> arithmetic</title>
	<p>
	Similarly to <xref ref="example-equiv-rel-even-and-odd-mod-2" />,
	if we consider the modulo-<m>n</m> equivalence relation <m>\mathord{\equiv}_n</m> on <m>\N</m>,
	we have
	<me> (\N / \mathord{\equiv}_n) = \{ \eqclass{0}, \eqclass{1}, \eqclass{2}, \dotsc, \eqclass{n-1} \} </me>.
	We can transfer the arithmetic of <m>\N</m> to <m>\N / \mathord{\equiv}_n</m> by defining
	<md><mrow>
		\eqclass{m} + \eqclass{n} \amp = \eqclass{m + n} \text{,} \amp
		\eqclass{m} \cdot \eqclass{n} \amp = \eqclass{m n} \text{.}
	</mrow></md>
	For example, in modulo-<m>5</m> arithmetic,
	<me> \eqclass{2} + \eqclass{4} = \eqclass{6} = \eqclass{1} </me>
	and <me> \eqclass{2} \cdot \eqclass{4} = \eqclass{8} = \eqclass{3} </me>.
	</p>
</example>

<exercise>
	<title>(Bonus content) Properties of modulo-<m>n</m> arithmetic</title>
	<p>
	There are a few things to check about this new modulo-<m>n</m> arithmetic.
	<ol>
		<li>
			Check that modulo-<m>n</m> addition and multiplication are <term>well-defined</term>;
			that is, make sure the result of each of these operations never depends on the choices of representatives of the equivalence classes involved.
		</li>
		<li>
			Check that modulo-<m>n</m> addition and multiplication satisfy all the usual rules of arithmetic.
			That is, check that modulo-<m>n</m> addition and multiplication are both <term>associative</term> and <term>commutative</term>,
			and that multiplication distributes over addition.
		</li>
		<li>
			The natural numbers <m>0</m> and <m>1</m> play special roles in <m>\N</m> with respect to ordinary addition and multiplication, respectively.
			Do their equivalence classes <m>\eqclass{0}</m> and <m>\eqclass{1}</m> play the same special roles in <m>\N / \mathrel{\equiv}_n</m> with respect to modulo-<m>n</m> addition and multiplication, respectively?
		</li>
	</ol>
</p></exercise>

<example xml:id="example-equiv-rel-eq-func-image">
	<title>Same image under a function</title>
	<p>
	For a function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m>,
	we may consider elements of the domain equivalent if they produce the same output under <m>f</m>.
	That is, the relation <m>\mathord{\equiv}_f</m> on <m>A</m> defined by <q><m>a_1 \equiv_f a_2</m> means <m>f(a_1) = f(a_2)</m></q> is an equivalence relation.
	</p>
</example>

<exercise>
	<title>Classes of the <q>same image</q> relation for an injective function</title>
	<p>
	Suppose <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> is a function, and consider the equivalence relation <m>\mathord{\equiv}_f</m> on <m>A</m> described in <xref ref="example-equiv-rel-eq-func-image" />.
	How could one tell whether or not <m>f</m> is injective by looking at the equivalence classes in <m>A</m> under <m>\mathord{\equiv}_f</m>?
	</p>
</exercise>

<example>
	<title>Inverting a non-injective function</title>
	<p>
	Equivalence relations allow us to take another point of view of the concept of
	<xref ref="definition-funcs-inverse-element-image" text="custom">inverse image of an element</xref>
	from <xref ref="section-funcs-inverses" />.
	</p><p>
	Suppose <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m>,
	and consider the equivalence relation <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m> on <m>A</m> described in
	<xref ref="example-equiv-rel-eq-func-image" />.
	Then we may create a new, <q>induced</q> function
	<md>
		<mrow>\tilde{f} \colon (A / \equiv) \amp \to B, </mrow>
		<mrow>\eqclass{a} \amp \mapsto f(a). </mrow>
	</md>
	</p>
	<figure>
		<caption>Diagram illustrating the induced map <m>\tilde{f}</m>.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-equiv-rel-induced-quotient-map" width="66.1%">
			<description>Diagram illustrating an induced map on a quotient</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="equiv-rel.d/induced-quotient-map.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
	<p>
	In this function definition, an entire equivalence class is being mapped to the output image of one of the elements of that class under the original function <m>f</m>.
	But under this equivalence relation, each element in a specific equivalence class shares the same output image in the codomain as all the other elements in that class.
	For this reason, allowing our <xref ref="definition-funcs-rule" text="title" /> definition
	<m>\tilde{f}\bbrac{\eqclass{a}} = f(a)</m>
	to depend on the choice of class representative <m>a</m> is <term>well-defined</term>,
	and hence <em>is</em> a function.
	</p>
	<aside><title>See</title><p> <xref ref="example-funcs-well-defined" />. </p></aside>
	<p>
	Moreover, the induced function <m>\tilde{f}</m> is always injective,
	even if <m>f</m> is not.
	If we assume that <m>f</m> is surjective
	(or, if <m>f</m> is not surjective we could replace our codomain <m>B</m> with the image set <m>f(A)</m> so that <m>f</m> <em>is</em> surjective <mdash />
	see <xref ref="definition-funcs-restricting-domain" text="title" />),
	then <m>\tilde{f}</m> will also be surjective, hence <em>bijective</em>.
	This means that <m>\tilde{f}</m> is invertible, with inverse
	<md>
		<mrow> \inv{\tilde{f}} \colon B \amp \to (A / \mathord{\equiv}_f), </mrow>
		<mrow> b \amp \mapsto \setdef{a\in A}{ f(a) = b } = \inv{f}\bbrac{\{b\}}. </mrow>
	</md>
	In some sense <m>\inv{\tilde{f}}</m> is an inverse of <m>f</m>,
	except that it is a function <m>B \to (A / \mathord{\equiv}_f) </m> instead of <m>B \to A</m>.
	</p>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-equiv-rel-graphs">
<title>Graph for an equivalence relation</title>

<p>
Given an equivalence relation on a finite set <m>A</m>,
what will we observe if we draw the relation's graph?
<ul>
	<li> Since an equivalence relation is reflexive, we might as well omit the loops at each node. </li>
	<li>
		Since an equivalence relation is symmetric,
		we might as well replace the pairs of arrows between each related pair of nodes with a single edge,
		turning the directed graph into an ordinary graph.
	</li>
	<li>
		Since an equivalence relation partitions a set into a disjoint union of equivalence classes
		(<xref ref="theorem-equiv-rel-classes-form-partition" />),
		the graph of an equivalence relation will be disconnected,
		with each connected component representing a specific equivalence class.
	</li>
	<li>
		Since each element in an equivalence class is equivalent to every other element in the class
		(<xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties-same-class-equivalent" text="type-local">Statement</xref>
		of <xref ref="proposition-equiv-rel-properties" />),
		each connected component in the graph will be complete.
	</li>
</ul>
</p>

<example>
	<title>Graph of the <q>same cardinality</q> equivalence relation</title>
	<p>
	Let <m>A = \{a,b,c,d\}</m>, and let <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m> be the equivalence relation on <m>\powset{A}</m> defined by <m>B \equiv B'</m> if <m>\card{B} = \card{B'}</m>.
	That is, two subsets of <m>A</m> will be considered equivalent if they contain the same number of elements.
	<xref ref="figure-equiv-rel-graph-same-cardinality" /> contains the graph for <m>\mathord{\equiv}</m>,
	with reflexive loops and symmetric bidirectional arrows omitted.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-equiv-rel-graph-same-cardinality">
		<caption>Graph for equivalence of cardinality on a power set.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-equiv-rel-graph-same-cardinality" width="67.9%">
			<description>Graph for equivalence of cardinality on a power set.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="equiv-rel.d/graph-same-cardinality.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
</example>

</section>

<xi:include href="./equiv-rel.d/activities.ptx" />
<xi:include href="./equiv-rel.d/exercises.ptx" />

</chapter>
